  'alloc.result.explainer.summary': 'How the score and ranking are computed',
  'alloc.result.explainer.body': '<p>Each org is evaluated across <strong>45 independent filters</strong> grouped into the form sections (regulatory, architecture, capacity, integrations, packages, backup, team, cost, etc.). Each filter returns <code>pass</code>, <code>warn</code> or <code>fail</code>.</p><p><strong>Numeric score</strong> — linear sum per filter:</p><ul><li><code>pass</code> = <strong>+3</strong></li><li><code>warn</code> = <strong>+1</strong></li><li><code>fail</code> = <strong>-2</strong></li></ul><p><strong>Criticality weighting</strong> — only the negative side scales. A <code>fail</code> on a <code>critical</code> process counts as <strong>3x</strong>; on <code>high</code>, 2x; on <code>medium</code>, 1x (reference); on <code>low</code>, 0.5x. <code>pass</code>/<code>warn</code> are worth the same at any criticality. Rationale: a legal blocker on a critical process is much more serious than on a low-priority one, but a good fit is not "better" because of criticality.</p><p>Practical range: 80-130 is an org with complete data and few caveats; 40-70 indicates that many fields were left empty (not a sign of a "bad org", but a sign of "missing information"). The raw score <code>scoreRaw</code> (without weighting) is available for reference.</p><p><strong>Aggregate status (<code>overall</code>)</strong> is <em>independent of the score</em>: a <strong>single filter</strong> in <code>fail</code> is enough for the entire org to be <code>fail</code>; otherwise, <code>warn</code> if there is any warn, otherwise <code>pass</code>.</p><p><strong>Ranking</strong> happens in two passes:</p><ol><li>Status first: <code>pass</code> &lt; <code>warn</code> &lt; <code>fail</code> — an org in <code>pass</code> with a low score <em>always</em> comes before an org in <code>warn</code> with a high score.</li><li>The weighted score breaks ties between orgs of the same status.</li></ol><p><strong>Remaining limitation:</strong> filters still weigh the same relative to one another — a <code>regulator=fail</code> (legal blocker) counts the same as a <code>documentation=fail</code>. The score is <strong>directional</strong>. The architectural reading requires looking at which filters failed, not just the number.</p>',
